<subSubSection id="56210C50E9917BAB60B099FC17ED99CC" pageId="13" pageNumber="100" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="A6DB7635C28D9AB1EA58742FC1AECFFA" pageId="13" pageNumber="100">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="32B74015E0CCAF117E7C00396C7201D7" pageId="13" pageNumber="100">
Female specimens at MNHN (Paris) were not available for study. This species is noteworthy in that the uncus is covered in shingled, scale-like clusters of setae (Figs 65, 127, 128), reminiscent of other fern-feeding species in the genus 
<taxonomicName id="B3C01F1342E883310FD7B19AD5ECBACA" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Lophomyra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lophomyra" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="100" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Lophomyra</taxonomicName>
. The relationship between these genera requires more thorough sampling and analysis of both taxa and genes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
